==English==

===Etymology===
First attested in the early 15th Century. From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|absolven|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|la|en}} {{term|absolvere|lang=la}}, present active infinitive of {{m|la|absolvō||set free, acquit}}, from {{term|ab||away from|lang=la}} + {{m|la|solvō||loosen, free, release}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|/əbˈzɒlv/|lang=en}}
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/æbˈzɑlv/|/æbˈsɑlv/|/əbˈzɑlv/|/əbˈsɑlv/|lang=en}}
* {{audio|en-us-absolve.ogg|Audio (US)|lang=en}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb|absolv|ing}}

# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To [[set free]], [[release]] or [[discharge]] (from [[obligation]]s, [[debt]]s, [[responsibility]] etc.). {{defdate|First attested around 1350 to 1470.}}<ref name=SOED>{{R:SOED5|page=9}}</ref>
#: ''You will '''absolve''' a subject from his allegiance.''
#* {{quote-book|year=1855|author=[[w:Thomas Babington Macaulay|Thomas Babington Macaulay]]|title=The History of England from the Accession of James II|volume=III|chapter-number=XIV|passage=Halifax was '''absolved''' by a majority of fourteen.}}
# {{context|transitive|obsolete|lang=en}} To [[resolve]]; to [[explain]]; to [[solve]]. {{defdate|Attested from the late 15<sup>th</sup> century until the mid 17<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>
#* {{quote-book|year=1646|author=[[w:Thomas Browne|Sir Thomas Browne]]|title=[[w:Pseudodoxia Epidemica|Pseudodoxia Epidemica]]|chapter-number=VI|page=x|url=http://penelope.uchicago.edu/pseudodoxia/pseudodoxia.shtml|passage=We shall not '''absolve''' the doubt.}}
# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To [[pronounce]] [[free]] from or give [[absolution]] for a [[penalty]], [[blame]], or [[guilt]]. {{defdate|First attested in the mid 16<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>
# {{context|transitive|legal|lang=en}} To pronounce not guilty; to grant a [[pardon]] for. {{defdate|First attested in the mid 16<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>
#* {{quote-book|year=1807|author=[[w:Alexander Pope]]|title=The Odyssey by Homer (English translation)|passage='''Absolves''' the just, and dooms the guilty souls.}}
# {{context|transitive|theology|lang=en}} To grant a remission of sin; to give [[absolution]] to. {{defdate|First attested in the mid 16<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>
#* {{quote-book|year=1597|author=[[w:William Shakespeare]]|title=Romeo and Juliet|section=Act 3, Scene 5| passage=To make confession and to be '''absolved'''.}}
# {{context|transitive|theology|lang=en}} To remit a sin; to give absolution for a sin. {{defdate|First attested in the late 16<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>
#* {{quote-book|year=1782|author=[[w:Edward Gibbon|Edward Gibbon]]|title=History Of The Decline And Fall Of The Roman Empire|volume=VI|chapter-number=LXVII|passage=In his name I '''absolve''' your perjury and sanctify your arms.}}
# {{context|transitive|obsolete|lang=en}} To [[finish]]; to [[accomplish]]. {{defdate|Attested from the late 16<sup>th</sup> century until the early 19<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>
#* {{RQ:Milton Lost|VII}}, line 94
#*: and the work begun, how soon '''absolv’d''',
# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To pass a course or test; to gain credit for a class; to qualify academically.

